## The Mission

Wine tasting has been around since the creation of wine itself. However, in the modern era, more importance has been given to drinking a _good_ wine, e.g. a french _Bordeaux_. France has always been hailed as the _land of the wine_.
However, during the [Judgment of Paris](<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Judgment_of_Paris_(wine)>) in 1976, a Californian wine scored better than a french wine which led to the increase in popularity of Californian wine.

Moreover, it has been shown that there are [many biases in wine tasting](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blind_wine_tasting).

That is why we put together this project to let an AI predict the quality of a wine.

## The Dataset

The dataset `wine.csv` is available here :  [./data/wine.csv](./data/wine.csv)

This one contains `6.497 observations` about wines (red and white).

For each of them, you have information `11 features` about the acidity, sugar, alcohol ... 
and the `quality` which will be our `target` and has the following repartition.

3. <u>Citric acid</u> is one of the fixed acids that you‚Äôll find in wines. 
   It‚Äôs expressed in *ùëî*/*ùëëùëö*<sup>3</sup>.

4. Residual sugar typically refers to the sugar remaining after fermentation stops, or is stopped.

6. <u>Free sulfur dioxide:</u> the part of the sulfur dioxide that is added to a wine and that is lost into it is said to be bound, while the  active part is said to be free. The winemaker will always try to get the highest proportion of free sulfur to bind.

8. Density is generally used as a measure of the conversion of sugar to alcohol. 
   It‚Äôs expressed in *ùëî*/*ùëê**ùëö*<sup>3</sup>

  > With a pH of 7, pure water is neutral. 
  > Most wines have a pH  between 2.9 and 3.9 and are therefore acidic.

10. Sulfates are to wine as gluten is to food. 
    You might already know sulfites from the headaches that they can cause. They are a regular  part of the winemaking around the world and are considered necessary.

    It‚Äôs expressed in *% vol*

12. Quality: wine experts graded the wine quality between 0 (very  bad) and 10 (very excellent). 
    The eventual number is the median of at  least three evaluations made by those same wine experts.




## The Experimentation

### Baseline model

Before testing a lot of model it's seems important to define a baseline model.
In this case, we build a simple neural network with the following properties :

- 2 hidden layers
- 10 neurons by hidden layers
- hidden activation function `relu` 
- output activation function `softmax`
- optimizer `Adam`
- loss function `MSE`

![img](data:image/png;base64,)

|                | ***Train*** | ***Test*** |
| -------------- | ----------- | ---------- |
| ***Loss***     | 0.0847      | 0.0863     |
| ***Accuracy*** | 52.76 %     | 51.54 %    |

As we can see on the following graph, the predicted values are concentrated on the most representatives data from our original dataset. `[5, 6, 7]`

![img](data:image/png;base64,)
